{
  "title": "Matrix Inversion",
  "summary": "Definition of the matrix inverse, inverse of 2×2 via formula, inverse of n×n via adjoint matrix, singularity condition, and laws of matrix algebra.",
  "widget_type": "variables",
  "position": 5,
  "is_published": true,
  "content_html": "<style>\n.mat{display:inline-grid;border-left:3px solid #94a3b8;border-right:3px solid #94a3b8;padding:6px 12px;gap:4px 16px;border-radius:2px;background:#1e293b;vertical-align:middle}\n.mat td{text-align:right;font-family:monospace;font-size:.95em;color:#e2e8f0;min-width:24px}\n.mat-eq-block{background:#0f172a;border:1px solid #334155;border-radius:8px;padding:16px 20px;margin:12px 0;display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;align-items:center;gap:12px}\n.mat-named{display:inline-flex;flex-direction:column;align-items:center;gap:4px}\n.mat-label{font-size:.78em;color:#64748b;font-family:monospace}\n.op{font-size:1.2em;font-weight:700;color:#94a3b8;padding:0 4px}\n.eq{font-size:1.2em;font-weight:700;color:#38bdf8;padding:0 4px}\n.formula-box{background:#0f172a;border:1px solid #334155;border-radius:8px;padding:12px 20px;margin:10px 0;font-family:monospace;font-size:1em;color:#f1f5f9;text-align:center}\n.note-box{background:#1a2e1a;border-left:4px solid #22c55e;border-radius:4px;padding:10px 16px;margin:10px 0;color:#bbf7d0;font-size:.93em}\n.def-box{background:#1e293b;border-left:4px solid #38bdf8;border-radius:4px;padding:10px 16px;margin:10px 0}\n.warn-box{background:#2d1f1f;border-left:4px solid #ef4444;border-radius:4px;padding:10px 16px;margin:10px 0;color:#fca5a5;font-size:.93em}\n.step-table{width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:10px 0;font-family:monospace;font-size:.9em}\n.step-table td,.step-table th{border:1px solid #334155;padding:6px 10px;color:#e2e8f0}\n.step-table th{background:#1e293b;color:#7dd3fc}\n.step-table tr:nth-child(even) td{background:#0f172a}\n.sign-grid{display:inline-grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(3,1fr);gap:4px;background:#1e293b;border:1px solid #334155;border-radius:6px;padding:10px;font-family:monospace;font-size:1.1em;text-align:center}\n.sign-plus{color:#22c55e;font-weight:700}\n.sign-minus{color:#ef4444;font-weight:700}\n</style>\n<h3>1.5 Matrix Inversion</h3>\n<div class=\"def-box\"><strong>Definition 1.24:</strong> If AB = I and BA = I, then B is the <strong>inverse</strong> of A, written A<sup>−1</sup>. The inverse exists only if A is square and non-singular.</div>\n\n<h4>Inverse of a 2×2 Matrix</h4>\n<div class=\"formula-box\">A = [a,b; c,d] &nbsp;→&nbsp; A<sup>−1</sup> = 1/det(A) · [d,−b; −c,a]</div>\n\n<div class=\"note-box\">det(A) = ad − bc must be ≠ 0. If det(A) = 0, A is <strong>singular</strong> and has no inverse.</div>\n\n<p><strong>Example 1.15:</strong> A = [[8,2],[4,3]]</p>\n<div class=\"mat-eq-block\">\n  <span style=\"color:#94a3b8\">det(A) = 24−8 = 16</span>\n  <span class=\"eq\">→</span>\n  <div class=\"mat-named\">\n    <span style=\"color:#94a3b8;font-size:.85em\">A<sup>−1</sup> = 1/16 ×</span>\n    <table class=\"mat\" style=\"display:inline-grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(2,1fr)\">\n      <tr><td>3</td><td>−2</td></tr><tr><td>−4</td><td>8</td></tr>\n    </table>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<h4>Inverse of n×n Matrix via Adjoint</h4>\n<div class=\"formula-box\">A<sup>−1</sup> = adj(A) / det(A) &nbsp;where&nbsp; adj(A) = C<sup>T</sup> (transpose of cofactor matrix)</div>\n\n<p><strong>Example 1.16:</strong> A = [[1,2,3],[7,5,6],[4,8,9]]</p>\n<div class=\"mat-eq-block\" style=\"flex-direction:column;align-items:flex-start;gap:8px\">\n  <div>\n    <span style=\"color:#7dd3fc\">Step 1: Cofactor matrix C</span>\n    <div class=\"mat-eq-block\" style=\"margin-top:6px\">\n      <table class=\"mat\" style=\"display:inline-grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(3,1fr)\">\n        <tr><td>−3</td><td>−39</td><td>36</td></tr>\n        <tr><td>6</td><td>−3</td><td>0</td></tr>\n        <tr><td>−3</td><td>15</td><td>−9</td></tr>\n      </table>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div>\n    <span style=\"color:#7dd3fc\">Step 2: adj(A) = C<sup>T</sup></span>\n    <div class=\"mat-eq-block\" style=\"margin-top:6px\">\n      <table class=\"mat\" style=\"display:inline-grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(3,1fr)\">\n        <tr><td>−3</td><td>6</td><td>−3</td></tr>\n        <tr><td>−39</td><td>−3</td><td>15</td></tr>\n        <tr><td>36</td><td>0</td><td>−9</td></tr>\n      </table>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div>\n    <span style=\"color:#7dd3fc\">Step 3: det(A) = 1(−3) − 2(63−24) + 3(56−20) = −3 − 78 + 108 = <strong style=\"color:#22c55e\">27</strong></span>\n  </div>\n  <div>\n    <span style=\"color:#7dd3fc\">Step 4: A<sup>−1</sup> = adj(A)/27</span>\n    <div class=\"mat-eq-block\" style=\"margin-top:6px\">\n      <table class=\"mat\" style=\"display:inline-grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(3,1fr)\">\n        <tr><td>−1/9</td><td>2/9</td><td>−1/9</td></tr>\n        <tr><td>−13/9</td><td>−1/9</td><td>5/9</td></tr>\n        <tr><td>4/3</td><td>0</td><td>−1/3</td></tr>\n      </table>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<h4>1.6 Laws of Matrix Algebra</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>If AB = I then B = A<sup>−1</sup> and A = B<sup>−1</sup></li>\n  <li>(A<sup>−1</sup>)<sup>−1</sup> = A</li>\n  <li>(kA)<sup>−1</sup> = k<sup>−1</sup>A<sup>−1</sup></li>\n  <li>(A<sup>T</sup>)<sup>−1</sup> = (A<sup>−1</sup>)<sup>T</sup></li>\n  <li>det(A<sup>−1</sup>) = 1/det(A)</li>\n  <li><strong>(AB)<sup>−1</sup> = B<sup>−1</sup>A<sup>−1</sup></strong> (reverse order!)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"warn-box\"><strong>Warning:</strong> (AB)<sup>−1</sup> = B<sup>−1</sup>A<sup>−1</sup> NOT A<sup>−1</sup>B<sup>−1</sup> — order is reversed!</div>\n\n<p><strong>Example 1.17:</strong> If BACD = I, express A in terms of inverses.<br>\nB<sup>−1</sup>BACD = ACD = B<sup>−1</sup> → AC = B<sup>−1</sup>D<sup>−1</sup> → A = B<sup>−1</sup>D<sup>−1</sup>C<sup>−1</sup></p>\n",
